# Widget Component Extraction Rule

## Overview
Large widget classes should be split into smaller, focused component widgets to improve code maintainability and readability.

## Guideline
Extract logical UI parts of a widget into separate private widget classes when:
- The component has complex logic
- The component is visually distinct
- The component might be reused or modified separately

## Examples

### ✅ Correct implementation:
```dart
class ProfileCard extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Container(
      child: Row(
        children: [
          _ProfileAvatar(avatarUrl: profile.avatarUrl),
          _ProfileInfo(name: profile.name, balance: profile.balance),
          _ActionButton(onTap: onAction),
        ],
      ),
    );
  }
}

class _ProfileAvatar extends StatelessWidget {
  final String? avatarUrl;
  
  const _ProfileAvatar({required this.avatarUrl});
  
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    // Avatar implementation
  }
}
```

### ❌ Incorrect implementation:
```dart
class ProfileCard extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Container(
      child: Row(
        children: [
          _buildAvatar(),
          _buildProfileInfo(),
          _buildActionButton(),
        ],
      ),
    );
  }
  
  Widget _buildAvatar() {
    // Avatar implementation
  }
  
  Widget _buildProfileInfo() {
    // Profile info implementation
  }
  
  Widget _buildActionButton() {
    // Action button implementation
  }
}
```

## Benefits
- Improved code organization
- Better separation of concerns
- Easier to understand and maintain
- More focused widget rebuilds
- More testable components